<header>
<h1>Can Police Refuse to Register an FIR in India?</h1>
<p class="author-line">
<strong>By Nikhil Chugh, Advocate | Supreme Court Bar Association Member | Panipat District Court</strong>
</p>
<a href="legal-insights.html" class="btn">← Back to Legal Insights</a>
</header>

<section>

<p>
The First Information Report (FIR) is the starting point of criminal investigation in India. It formally records information regarding the commission of a cognizable offence and allows the police to initiate investigation. However, many citizens often face a situation where the police refuse to register an FIR.
</p>

<p>
This raises an important legal question: <strong>Can the police legally refuse to register an FIR?</strong>
</p>

<h2>1. FIR Registration in Cognizable Offences is Mandatory</h2>

<p>
Under <strong>Section 173 of the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023 (BNSS)</strong> (earlier Section 154 of the Criminal Procedure Code), registration of an FIR is mandatory when information discloses the commission of a cognizable offence.
</p>

<p>
A cognizable offence is a serious offence where the police have the authority to register a case and begin investigation without prior court approval. Examples include offences such as theft, assault, kidnapping, and murder.
</p>

<h2>2. Supreme Court Ruling in Lalita Kumari Case</h2>

<p>
The Supreme Court of India clarified the law in the landmark case of <strong>Lalita Kumari v. Government of Uttar Pradesh (2013)</strong>.
</p>

<p>
The Court held that registration of FIR is <strong>mandatory</strong> when information reveals a cognizable offence. Police authorities cannot conduct a preliminary inquiry in such cases to avoid registration.
</p>

<p>
Failure to register an FIR in such circumstances can amount to dereliction of duty.
</p>

<h2>3. What If Police Refuse to Register an FIR?</h2>

<p>
If a police officer refuses to record your complaint, the law provides several remedies:
</p>

<p>
<strong>Approach the Superintendent of Police (SP):</strong> A written complaint can be submitted to the SP of the district requesting registration of the FIR.
</p>

<p>
<strong>File a complaint before the Magistrate:</strong> Under criminal procedure law, a Magistrate can direct the police to register the FIR and investigate the case.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Send complaint through registered post:</strong> Written complaints sent to higher police authorities often trigger official action.
</p>

<h2>4. Concept of Zero FIR</h2>

<p>
Another important safeguard available to citizens is the concept of <strong>Zero FIR</strong>.
</p>

<p>
A Zero FIR can be registered at any police station regardless of jurisdiction. The police station receiving the complaint must register the FIR and later transfer it to the appropriate jurisdictional police station.
</p>

<p>
This mechanism is particularly important in urgent cases such as serious crimes or offences against women.
</p>

<h2>5. Why Legal Awareness is Important</h2>

<p>
Awareness of FIR registration rights empowers citizens and ensures accountability in law enforcement. The criminal justice system relies on proper reporting of offences, and refusal to register FIRs undermines the rule of law.
</p>

<p>
Citizens should therefore be aware that police officers are legally obligated to register FIRs in cognizable offences and that remedies exist when authorities fail to perform this duty.
</p>

<p>
Legal awareness strengthens democracy and ensures that justice remains accessible to every citizen.
</p>

